1 For example, Miller and Johnson-Laird (1976), Talmy (1983), Jackendoff (1983) and Lakoff (1987) and Svorou (1994).
2 English, Swedish, Spanish, Italian, Serbo-Croatian and Bulgarian, and 3 non-IE languages: Finnish, Estonian and Japanese, supplemented with the analysis of secondary data from languages, whose spatial systems are reputedly difficult for universalist analyses: Archi (Dagestanian), Ewe (West-African) and Tzeltal (Mayan).
3 This does not imply an “objectivist” semantics, since e.g. The tree is by the car and The car is by the tree correspond to different situations when these are understood as representing the lived world of human experience, rather than the “real world”.
4 Thai informants vary immensely on their tolerance of e.g. (8b) – from acceptance to complete rejection, but even those who accept it, state that the sentence is better either without pay (8a) or with the Region noun nay (kha^w pay nay hç^çN). This fact will be addressed in Section 5.

